{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6dce17d1-bf75-415f-b251-7ae89ec96e37","content":"Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>()`. In MSTest v3 it returns the cast instance, combining the type check, null check, and cast in one call:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()\n{\n    var factory = new HandlerFactory();\n    var result = factory.Create(\"email\");\n\n    var handler = Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);\n    Assert.AreEqual(\"email\", handler.Type);\n}\n```\n\nThis gives you a clear failure message if the type is wrong (instead of an `InvalidCastException`), and eliminates the separate `IsNotNull` check.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"28e76f7a-2677-49ff-bef8-15a2347d97e6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a better MSTest assertion for checking the returned type instead of hard casting. This is about MSTest-specific assertion guidance.\n\nThe answer is `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>()` which was introduced in MSTest v2/v3. It returns the cast object, so you can use it directly.\n\nIn MSTest v3+, there's `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>(object actual, out T instance)` - actually let me think about this more carefully.\n\nIn MSTest v2, `Assert.IsInstanceOfType(object value, Type expectedType)` exists but doesn't return the typed value.\n\n\nI'm trying to pin down exactly which MSTest version introduced the generic overload that returns the typed value, since the behavior seems to have evolved across v2 and v3 releases.","outputTokens":545,"requestId":"EBCA:4D1EE:785F97:7FFDBD:6A044E15"},"id":"08b41413-4f6b-4de5-97eb-38068e3bf1a3","timestamp":"2026-05-13T10:10:44.142Z","parentId":"f684d5e3-a91a-4af9-9383-28a04b67f397"}
